1
00:00:42,286 --> 00:00:43,167
Greetings all.

2
00:00:44,088 --> 00:00:44,709
Very good.

3
00:00:45,670 --> 00:00:50,956
There are, at the moment, 66 people, all looking at me, for heaven's sake.

4
00:00:54,118 --> 00:00:54,899
That's very lovely.

5
00:00:56,121 --> 00:01:00,006
So, I just start in my usual way.

6
00:01:02,368 --> 00:01:09,897
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

7
00:01:10,618 --> 00:01:35,685
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

8
00:01:36,887 --> 00:01:38,128
I'm presuming you can hear me.

9
00:01:39,087 --> 00:01:40,849
So it's good to have a little test there.

10
00:01:43,132 --> 00:01:47,640
Somebody could say, they could just give me a nod to say they can hear me.

11
00:01:47,700 --> 00:01:53,188
That would be, that would lessen my sense of overwhelming anxiety.

12
00:01:54,831 --> 00:01:55,972
Nobody's answering.

13
00:01:58,996 --> 00:02:00,700
Well, I'm just presuming you can hear me.

14
00:02:02,563 --> 00:02:03,703
Yes, I'll have to presume.

15
00:02:05,527 --> 00:02:07,390
So I hope you had a fruitful day.

16
00:02:08,634 --> 00:02:09,596
Very good.

17
00:02:09,635 --> 00:02:10,236
Loud and clear.

18
00:02:10,276 --> 00:02:10,997
Thank you so much.

19
00:02:11,138 --> 00:02:11,538
Very good.

20
00:02:11,598 --> 00:02:12,259
Audio is great.

21
00:02:12,560 --> 00:02:12,819
Right.

22
00:02:13,020 --> 00:02:13,381
I'm with it.

23
00:02:16,525 --> 00:02:17,006
Yeah, that's enough.

24
00:02:17,026 --> 00:02:17,586
Thank you very much.

25
00:02:17,646 --> 00:02:28,180
So, yes, hopefully you've had a fruitful day.

26
00:02:28,783 --> 00:02:38,675
Just to reiterate, if you want to have, if something comes up which is a bit heavy for you to handle, feel free to get in touch.

27
00:02:39,356 --> 00:02:47,026
Use my email, bbbodhi, bbodhi, at gmail.com.

28
00:02:47,086 --> 00:02:49,329
Sometimes it's good just to talk to somebody.

29
00:02:49,628 --> 00:02:58,740
I'm thinking, obviously, especially for those people who find themselves locked in by themselves, that can be a bit of a miserable state.

30
00:02:59,092 --> 00:03:02,978
Although these days it's lessened with all the social media.

31
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:05,081
It's a blessing, really.

32
00:03:09,127 --> 00:03:09,588
So...

33
00:03:19,844 --> 00:03:22,128
I'm just making sure I'm actually...

34
00:03:36,502 --> 00:03:37,783
Yeah.

35
00:03:37,804 --> 00:03:39,425
Sorry, I wasn't plugged in properly.

36
00:03:41,807 --> 00:03:45,891
I've got to get used to all this stuff, you know.

37
00:03:45,912 --> 00:03:57,021
So I just wanted to... Oh, by the way, the little talk I give in the evenings, you'll find them as separate little items on the channel.

38
00:03:58,163 --> 00:04:05,650
So that if you happen to miss some of my pearls of wisdom one night, you can always check it out

39
00:04:06,051 --> 00:04:06,913
in the daytime.

40
00:04:09,074 --> 00:04:09,495
Okay.

41
00:04:10,975 --> 00:04:14,218
So I wanted to answer these questions that were sent to me.

42
00:04:14,278 --> 00:04:23,346
To what extent can it be argued that the Four Noble Truths was the Buddha's most important teaching?

43
00:04:24,307 --> 00:04:26,209
Sounds a bit like one of these A-level questions.

44
00:04:29,632 --> 00:04:33,156
And are all the stages of the Eightfold Path equally important?

45
00:04:33,896 --> 00:04:34,336
Now,

46
00:04:34,586 --> 00:04:50,903
This discourse, which is the Samaditti, the right view discourse, where Sariputta is being asked, basically, what do we need to understand?

47
00:04:50,985 --> 00:04:55,468
What right view do we need to have in order to become liberated?

48
00:04:55,889 --> 00:05:01,776
And he gives various answers to that.

49
00:05:01,992 --> 00:05:08,742
And there's a sort of suggestion that if you understand any of these fully, that would lead to liberation.

50
00:05:09,423 --> 00:05:15,653
Now, that only makes sense when we realize that the teaching, the Dharma, is all one piece, really.

51
00:05:16,295 --> 00:05:22,024
Once you investigate one part of it, it naturally leads you to other parts.

52
00:05:24,728 --> 00:05:29,855
Anyway, he's being asked again, but friend, might there be another way?

53
00:05:30,476 --> 00:05:36,524
in which a noble disciple is of right view and has arrived at this true Dharma.

54
00:05:36,545 --> 00:05:37,725
And he says, yes, there is.

55
00:05:38,286 --> 00:05:43,252
And then there is what you might call a regular expression of the Four Noble Truths.

56
00:05:43,612 --> 00:05:44,735
So I'll read those out.

57
00:05:46,377 --> 00:05:48,699
What is the noble truth of suffering?

58
00:05:49,721 --> 00:05:51,403
What is the origin of suffering?

59
00:05:52,144 --> 00:05:54,105
What is the cessation of suffering?

60
00:05:54,766 --> 00:05:57,911
And what is the way leading to the cessation of suffering?

61
00:05:57,930 --> 00:05:59,353
So there's your Four Noble Truths.

62
00:06:00,716 --> 00:06:01,877
Birth is suffering.

63
00:06:02,639 --> 00:06:03,699
Aging is suffering.

64
00:06:04,201 --> 00:06:05,341
Sickness is suffering.

65
00:06:06,523 --> 00:06:07,584
Death is suffering.

66
00:06:07,904 --> 00:06:12,569
Sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair are suffering.

67
00:06:13,451 --> 00:06:16,033
Not to obtain what one wants is suffering.

68
00:06:16,413 --> 00:06:22,019
In short, the five aggregates of effect of clinging are suffering.

69
00:06:22,439 --> 00:06:22,721
OK.

70
00:06:24,062 --> 00:06:25,202
So we'll take it one by one.

71
00:06:26,605 --> 00:06:29,007
Now, that's pretty straight.

72
00:06:29,187 --> 00:06:30,428
That's pretty straightforward, isn't it?

73
00:06:30,449 --> 00:06:30,588
I mean,

74
00:06:30,956 --> 00:06:36,382
The whole business of being born is not particularly pleasant either for the child and the mother.

75
00:06:37,083 --> 00:06:38,324
And then aging and all.

76
00:06:38,343 --> 00:06:40,586
So all of it is pretty straightforward.

77
00:06:41,007 --> 00:06:46,612
But then there's this little sentence, not obtaining what one wants.

78
00:06:47,052 --> 00:06:55,341
Now, there's your frustration, your anxiety that you might not get it, all that sort of stuff.

79
00:06:55,802 --> 00:06:59,125
Now, this word dukkha, that's what it's translating, suffering.

80
00:06:59,964 --> 00:07:03,668
These days, people prefer unsatisfactoriness.

81
00:07:05,391 --> 00:07:08,434
The word dukkha itself means just hard to bear.

82
00:07:08,494 --> 00:07:14,939
Du is like, it just means bad, not good.

83
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:18,023
And ka means to bear something.

84
00:07:18,043 --> 00:07:20,286
So it's something that's difficult to bear.

85
00:07:20,326 --> 00:07:27,033
And it's used figuratively, for instance, to describe an axle in a wheel, which doesn't quite fit.

86
00:07:27,093 --> 00:07:29,415
So you get the grinding noise, it doesn't quite fit.

87
00:07:30,862 --> 00:07:46,300
And what Dukkha, what the Buddha is saying, the way he's using the word is not just on these obvious things like, you know, ordinary sufferings and pains and all that sort of stuff.

88
00:07:47,180 --> 00:07:50,464
But there is this business of not getting what one wants.

89
00:07:51,406 --> 00:07:55,831
And that's to do with, you know, our desires, our expectations.

90
00:07:56,550 --> 00:07:59,875
So that obviously causes us a lot of suffering.

91
00:08:00,547 --> 00:08:03,129
But the next sentence goes a little deeper.

92
00:08:03,470 --> 00:08:08,494
It says the five aggregates affected by clinging are suffering.

93
00:08:09,314 --> 00:08:20,565
Now, those of you who know dependence origination will know the middle links, right, which connect, which expresses how we create this suffering.

94
00:08:20,665 --> 00:08:23,127
So remember, there is this point of contact.

95
00:08:23,848 --> 00:08:30,435
Then there's the discernment that what we're experiencing is pleasant or unpleasant.

96
00:08:30,735 --> 00:08:42,692
liking, disliking, and then of course we choose to grasp at or desire rather, desire what's pleasant and push away what's unpleasant.

97
00:08:42,712 --> 00:08:44,716
And that's the reaction, right?

98
00:08:45,035 --> 00:08:50,664
But it's the next one where we upadana, which means to cling, to get hold of, yeah?

99
00:08:52,567 --> 00:09:00,118
Now this upadana is manifest as in four different ways when I find a bit of paper.

100
00:09:01,465 --> 00:09:01,825
Yes.

101
00:09:06,831 --> 00:09:11,197
It's first of all a clinging to the pleasures of the senses.

102
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:13,280
That's the sort of clinging.

103
00:09:13,761 --> 00:09:18,908
And of course, if you are not being pleased, then your response is to get rid of it.

104
00:09:19,229 --> 00:09:24,235
So there's always this duality of aversion and desire.

105
00:09:24,576 --> 00:09:26,739
And the aversion, of course, splits into two.

106
00:09:26,759 --> 00:09:28,721
You either get rid of it or run from it.

107
00:09:29,511 --> 00:09:32,416
And then there's this holding onto views, opinions.

108
00:09:33,136 --> 00:09:34,899
I'm right, everybody else is wrong.

109
00:09:34,958 --> 00:09:36,240
That's also sort of clingy.

110
00:09:37,162 --> 00:09:39,605
Then there's this one about rules and regulations.

111
00:09:40,687 --> 00:09:51,240
This is really going back to an understanding of the time when ritual was a way of appeasing the gods or demanding the gods to do something.

112
00:09:51,761 --> 00:09:58,910
So if you think that, for instance, bowing to the Buddha, lighting candles and all that sort of stuff actually is going to liberate you,

113
00:09:59,245 --> 00:10:01,807
then you are definitely deluded.

114
00:10:01,827 --> 00:10:03,971
So that's the rules and regulations.

115
00:10:04,171 --> 00:10:14,062
But the one that I particularly reinforce when I'm talking about this is identity, because that's where the root cause is.

116
00:10:14,163 --> 00:10:16,666
The root cause is the sense of I.

117
00:10:16,706 --> 00:10:22,774
And that's really where the suffering becomes existential.

118
00:10:23,073 --> 00:10:25,336
It becomes a position of me.

119
00:10:25,890 --> 00:10:37,668
And that comes most obvious when death approaches us, but also serious illness or indeed the death of somebody we love or the serious illness of somebody we love.

120
00:10:38,048 --> 00:10:39,429
It impinges upon us.

121
00:10:39,529 --> 00:10:49,043
It begins to question our identity because this identity, this self, this feeling of me has a feeling about it of permanence.

122
00:10:49,283 --> 00:10:53,990
You know, like even though we're quite happy to get rid of it when we fall asleep,

123
00:10:54,307 --> 00:10:58,333
You know, there's the presumption that next morning I'm going to wake up and say, oh, here I am again.

124
00:10:58,634 --> 00:11:03,740
So that's the suffering.

125
00:11:03,801 --> 00:11:12,133
So it's pretty straightforward unsatisfactoriness, not being able to get fully satisfied with life.

126
00:11:12,232 --> 00:11:23,269
It's always going to let us down a bit, even when we've got everything, you know, the right house, the right car, the right partner, the right children, et cetera, et cetera, at some point.

127
00:11:23,535 --> 00:11:25,658
it just begins to disappear.

128
00:11:26,298 --> 00:11:27,659
And that's the way it is.

129
00:11:28,961 --> 00:11:31,924
Then there's the suffering, which is not getting what you want.

130
00:11:33,326 --> 00:11:39,893
And then there's the suffering, which is to do with this existential, this sense of self.

131
00:11:41,494 --> 00:11:52,125
So this word dukkha, this word dukkha, which is very difficult to define, very difficult to translate, excuse me, because it has such a wide meaning.

132
00:11:52,577 --> 00:11:59,405
And what the Buddha is really saying is that the whole of life, the whole of human life is unsatisfactory.

133
00:12:00,447 --> 00:12:10,076
And I always like the quote from Jesus on this when he said, the birds have their nipples, but the son of man has nowhere to rest his head.

134
00:12:10,697 --> 00:12:14,422
So I think that's put it very, very poetically, very beautifully.

135
00:12:18,365 --> 00:12:21,690
So then, of course, there's the there's the origin of suffering.

136
00:12:22,312 --> 00:12:24,235
or the cause of suffering.

137
00:12:24,715 --> 00:12:35,289
And that is, it is craving, which brings renewal of becoming, is accompanied by delight and lust, and delights in this and that.

138
00:12:35,910 --> 00:12:43,600
That is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for becoming, and craving for non-becoming.

139
00:12:43,620 --> 00:12:45,724
This is called the origin of suffering.

140
00:12:46,725 --> 00:12:51,272
It's translated it here as origin, but I would probably prefer the word

141
00:12:51,725 --> 00:12:54,470
a cause, the basic cause of suffering.

142
00:12:55,009 --> 00:13:09,774
So the word here that's being translated is tanha, which some authors, I think, probably are closer to the mark when you translate it as a thirst, a lack, a sense of lack.

143
00:13:09,794 --> 00:13:12,720
That's another translation that some authors use.

144
00:13:13,004 --> 00:13:14,605
And those get close to it.

145
00:13:14,745 --> 00:13:19,974
Craving is a bit too strong, craving, although we do have cravings.

146
00:13:21,075 --> 00:13:29,687
It's actually covering all desires, even from the simplest thing, like when you're watching TV and you feel a bit uncomfortable, there's a desire to move.

147
00:13:30,227 --> 00:13:41,322
So if you watch all your intentions, you'll see that they're all, normally speaking, desires to get rid of something you don't like or get something you do like.

148
00:13:43,143 --> 00:13:47,830
And so we're constantly manipulating the world to make ourselves feel comfortable.

149
00:13:49,572 --> 00:14:02,971
And it's accompanied, you see, with delight, and it's got lust here, but it's more like an indulgence, delight and indulgence.

150
00:14:08,759 --> 00:14:13,065
So the question that we have to ask ourselves,

151
00:14:13,754 --> 00:14:31,336
When I want something, when I want something or someone from this position of trying to escape suffering, because that's what we're doing when we're often indulging things and also enjoying it, what is it that we really want?

152
00:14:31,376 --> 00:14:42,171
Do we actually want the object we're desiring or the effect that the object has on us, right?

153
00:14:42,191 --> 00:14:42,650
Have a guess.

154
00:14:42,791 --> 00:14:43,272
What do you think?

155
00:14:46,711 --> 00:14:47,652
What is it we really want?

156
00:14:47,731 --> 00:14:53,697
I mean, do we really want porridge or do we want what porridge does to us?

157
00:14:55,038 --> 00:14:56,100
Toast, that's another one.

158
00:14:56,299 --> 00:14:58,020
Yeah, I know I'm a bit obsessive about toast.

159
00:14:59,802 --> 00:15:06,509
So it's trying to establish or trying to develop a certain mental state, isn't it?

160
00:15:06,729 --> 00:15:09,231
A certain emotional feeling state.

161
00:15:12,414 --> 00:15:16,177
And that's what this craving does or this thirst.

162
00:15:16,967 --> 00:15:21,293
Um, and it produces habits, produce habits.

163
00:15:21,693 --> 00:15:36,014
And what we discover in, um, on meditation and even now with this, uh, lockdown is that when you interrupt a habit, when you stop a habit, it suddenly becomes a choice.

164
00:15:36,914 --> 00:15:38,437
Normally we're running with habits.

165
00:15:38,716 --> 00:15:40,278
You know, you get up, you do this, you do that.

166
00:15:40,600 --> 00:15:41,821
You want a piece of toast.

167
00:15:41,841 --> 00:15:42,582
See, I'm at it again.

168
00:15:43,384 --> 00:15:44,105
Uh, and off you go.

169
00:15:44,125 --> 00:15:45,186
Uh,

170
00:15:45,368 --> 00:15:50,013
But when you can't, when there's no bread, you see, or when the toaster's broke, it's broken, isn't it?

171
00:15:50,033 --> 00:15:52,716
The habit's broken and it sort of comes back at you.

172
00:15:53,636 --> 00:15:56,899
And now most times we would fight that and run out and get a toaster.

173
00:15:57,500 --> 00:16:04,607
But it also gives us a choice, you see, a choice to bring about an end to that sort of compulsive behaviour.

174
00:16:05,909 --> 00:16:12,777
So if we look upon this lockdown, some of us are having to stay in, you know, in rooms, can't actually leave.

175
00:16:14,139 --> 00:16:19,105
This is an opportunity, really, to see where these obsessive-compulsive things are.

176
00:16:19,647 --> 00:16:21,068
And, of course, it can be difficult.

177
00:16:21,389 --> 00:16:22,390
It can be very difficult.

178
00:16:22,951 --> 00:16:35,706
But that's the whole reason for practicing this vipassana, that you find a different relationship with it so that you allow the heart to express its turbulences, no matter how difficult that may be.

179
00:16:36,388 --> 00:16:39,532
And what we discover, of course, is that that's the way it heals itself.

180
00:16:42,015 --> 00:16:43,977
So that's the origins.

181
00:16:44,177 --> 00:16:46,360
or the cause of suffering.

182
00:16:49,664 --> 00:16:51,746
Sorry, I'm not finished yet.

183
00:16:51,767 --> 00:16:54,190
There's also the craving for becoming.

184
00:16:55,812 --> 00:16:58,894
So there's yourself, you see, always wanting to become.

185
00:16:59,635 --> 00:17:02,320
And you'll notice how you're always ahead of yourself.

186
00:17:02,419 --> 00:17:12,852
You're always thinking about what you're going to do in a minute or in an hour or this afternoon or when you go to work or when you don't go to work or when you retire.

187
00:17:13,185 --> 00:17:13,445
Yeah.

188
00:17:13,465 --> 00:17:14,327
What are you going to do?

189
00:17:16,770 --> 00:17:19,934
So the self never feels safe just being in the present moment.

190
00:17:19,994 --> 00:17:24,080
He can't hold that position because it's unsafe.

191
00:17:24,121 --> 00:17:28,086
He doesn't know what's going to happen next, for heaven's sake.

192
00:17:28,106 --> 00:17:36,077
So this craving for constantly becoming and the other one is craving for non-becoming.

193
00:17:36,117 --> 00:17:42,686
So that's, of course, takes us to the dark side to put an end to this because of the suffering that we're having.

194
00:17:43,290 --> 00:17:44,833
leading towards suicide.

195
00:17:45,673 --> 00:17:46,374
That's the worst.

196
00:17:46,575 --> 00:17:50,898
Or if you're angry with somebody, murdering them because they're stopping you getting happy.

197
00:17:52,901 --> 00:17:56,605
But we've given that up, remember, because we take the five precepts, yeah?

198
00:17:58,386 --> 00:18:07,777
So that craving for becoming and craving for non-becoming, that digs deep again to this existential problem about who am I?

199
00:18:08,198 --> 00:18:09,638
And that's the question, who am I?

200
00:18:10,800 --> 00:18:11,981
Or what am I?

201
00:18:15,083 --> 00:18:19,326
And then finally, sorry, and then the third one is cessation of suffering.

202
00:18:20,407 --> 00:18:22,309
How does that come to an end?

203
00:18:22,410 --> 00:18:24,873
How does all this stuff come to an end?

204
00:18:24,972 --> 00:18:27,756
So this is the regular formula.

205
00:18:28,356 --> 00:18:39,928
It is the remainderless fading away and ceasing, the giving up, relinquishing, letting go and rejecting of that same craving.

206
00:18:41,849 --> 00:18:44,532
Just this is the end of suffering, the cessation of suffering.

207
00:18:44,917 --> 00:18:47,099
Now that sounds really simple, doesn't it?

208
00:18:47,401 --> 00:18:54,468
Just to give up the craving, give up all these obsessive desires, this compulsive behavior, and voila, you've made it.

209
00:18:55,689 --> 00:19:00,753
But of course, what we discovered is that that's no easy thing at all.

210
00:19:00,773 --> 00:19:12,546
And that comes very obvious when we go on retreat, just the difficulty of changing our habits completely.

211
00:19:13,150 --> 00:19:16,913
The first three days, as you know, are all blood, sweat and tears.

212
00:19:17,473 --> 00:19:20,698
And then it eases off a bit, but never a lot.

213
00:19:21,198 --> 00:19:22,499
And it's always been a struggle.

214
00:19:23,500 --> 00:19:25,643
So the practice is hard.

215
00:19:26,343 --> 00:19:28,705
The Buddha doesn't pull punches on that, you know.

216
00:19:29,405 --> 00:19:35,633
I'm sure you've heard me say, heard me quote from the scriptures there.

217
00:19:36,032 --> 00:19:39,916
Somebody says to the Buddha, you know, this training is very hard.

218
00:19:40,505 --> 00:19:44,910
And he says, well, he said, it is hard, but in the end, you're liberated, you achieve nibbana.

219
00:19:45,349 --> 00:19:46,912
And the questioner says, yeah, so what?

220
00:19:48,913 --> 00:19:53,898
And the Buddha says, well, at the end of it, you are happy and with it, contented.

221
00:19:55,359 --> 00:19:57,301
Tutti sukha wahati, tutti.

222
00:19:58,423 --> 00:20:01,385
That's the word for contentment, tutti.

223
00:20:02,247 --> 00:20:03,048
Tutti frutti.

224
00:20:07,813 --> 00:20:09,734
So that's this business of...

225
00:20:10,069 --> 00:20:10,851
the cessation.

226
00:20:13,094 --> 00:20:15,217
And the final one is, of course, the Eightfold Path.

227
00:20:15,498 --> 00:20:22,627
Now, the question is, can it be argued is the Buddha's most important teaching?

228
00:20:22,969 --> 00:20:36,248
Well, if you can imagine, when the Buddha had his awakening, and it was said he spent a week thinking about it, especially dependence origination, the psychology that he had discovered.

229
00:20:37,430 --> 00:20:39,772
And then he began teaching.

230
00:20:40,192 --> 00:20:57,988
The first part of the scriptures, which you'll see in, some of you might know the Nipata Sutta, which was translated by my Upajayu, Dr. Saratissa, Venerable Dr. Saratissa was the chief monk at the London Buddhist Vihara in the 80s.

231
00:20:58,827 --> 00:21:02,912
And when I ordained, he was my preceptor.

232
00:21:04,432 --> 00:21:08,477
So although all my meditation teachers were Burmese,

233
00:21:08,795 --> 00:21:14,503
My order was into one of the Sri Lankan orders.

234
00:21:16,747 --> 00:21:17,848
And he's translated it.

235
00:21:17,989 --> 00:21:20,353
It's a lovely translation, that, the Nipata Sutta.

236
00:21:21,253 --> 00:21:28,164
And Bhikkhu Bodhi has done a great big, huge volume, which translates the commentary as well.

237
00:21:28,625 --> 00:21:32,892
Now, the interesting thing about the Nipata Sutta is that it's pretty original.

238
00:21:33,492 --> 00:21:36,017
And that always surprises me, really, because

239
00:21:36,402 --> 00:21:39,646
you can see the original teaching wasn't so formalized.

240
00:21:39,807 --> 00:21:43,172
He's answering individual questions.

241
00:21:44,192 --> 00:21:49,019
And slowly, you know, the teaching becomes formalized.

242
00:21:49,059 --> 00:21:55,368
And that's when you get these, you know, four of these, ten of those, nine of them, and so on and so forth.

243
00:21:56,309 --> 00:21:58,673
And that formalization is the middle bit.

244
00:21:58,713 --> 00:22:04,501
And then it becomes, towards the end, it becomes very sort of listy, like,

245
00:22:04,819 --> 00:22:06,181
you know, to help you remember things.

246
00:22:06,361 --> 00:22:23,415
And it begins, you can see it begins to be a bit like the Abhidhamma, which was a later development, which takes away all that, all the, what would you call it, not humanity.

247
00:22:24,616 --> 00:22:31,722
When you read the scriptures, you do get the feeling of a person, the Buddha talking and people who are talking to him.

248
00:22:32,304 --> 00:22:33,865
And as the

249
00:22:34,232 --> 00:22:37,917
a teacher becomes more and more intellectualized, that begins to disappear.

250
00:22:38,278 --> 00:22:40,142
And it really does become lists.

251
00:22:41,222 --> 00:22:44,448
So there's these three waves of development.

252
00:22:45,148 --> 00:22:53,381
And it's interesting, I think, or surprising, shall I say, that the oral tradition maintained those very early teachings.

253
00:22:53,701 --> 00:22:54,201
They're there.

254
00:22:55,123 --> 00:22:58,468
And then, of course, you get this more formalized, the Four Noble Truths.

255
00:23:02,936 --> 00:23:09,669
So when he has finally formalized it, these Four Noble Truths are the foundation of the whole teaching.

256
00:23:10,349 --> 00:23:23,053
And you could say that if you come across any teaching, so-called Buddhism, which doesn't fit into the understanding of the Four Noble Truths, then it's not right.

257
00:23:23,133 --> 00:23:25,096
It's not particularly right.

258
00:23:25,853 --> 00:23:36,107
And each of these noble truths, of course, launch out into various other teachings and we'll come to some of them very much in this particular discourse.

259
00:23:37,230 --> 00:23:50,950
And so whenever you start, whenever you start to talk about karma, start talking about the body, doesn't matter where you start talking about what it is you start talking about, you always end up

260
00:23:51,182 --> 00:23:58,653
really investigating the whole of the Dharma because it just leads from links one to another until you've virtually covered it.

261
00:24:00,355 --> 00:24:04,520
And you'll always come down to this root level about dukkha.

262
00:24:04,721 --> 00:24:13,932
If you were going to encapsulate one word which expresses the Buddha's understanding of the human condition, that's the word dukkha.

263
00:24:15,734 --> 00:24:19,941
And if you...

264
00:24:20,073 --> 00:24:32,830
wanted to choose one word which encapsulates the fundamental problem that we have, it would be atta, self, teaching around not self.

265
00:24:33,872 --> 00:24:41,722
And if you were to choose one word which expresses the way out of it, the actual practice to get out of it, it would be sati, awareness.

266
00:24:41,963 --> 00:24:44,527
But you'd have to put sama in front of it.

267
00:24:44,807 --> 00:24:48,252
It's right awareness, yeah?

268
00:24:48,272 --> 00:24:49,994
It's a specific definition.

269
00:24:51,561 --> 00:24:56,829
So in other words, if you're thieving, you're fully aware, you know, but it's not going to get you liberated.

270
00:24:57,651 --> 00:24:58,893
It might make you rich for a little while.

271
00:25:01,436 --> 00:25:03,759
So that's the Four Noble.

272
00:25:03,779 --> 00:25:04,721
I'm just looking at the time.

273
00:25:04,922 --> 00:25:05,722
Oh, it's going on.

274
00:25:06,263 --> 00:25:11,952
So I want to leave it there, and then tomorrow we'll have a look at the stages.

275
00:25:12,673 --> 00:25:18,221
And the question is, are all the stages of the Eightfold Path equally important?

276
00:25:18,962 --> 00:25:20,826
So we can have a look at that tomorrow.

277
00:25:21,413 --> 00:25:21,772
Okay.

278
00:25:25,679 --> 00:25:26,098
Very good.

279
00:25:28,602 --> 00:25:34,230
So yesterday I forgot to take the refs and presets for those of you who would like to do it.

280
00:25:35,330 --> 00:25:41,159
And then once I've done that, we can sit and as usual, towards the end, I'll do these contemplations.

281
00:25:44,262 --> 00:25:44,603
Okay.

282
00:25:46,961 --> 00:25:59,861
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused even greater confusion, and that by your devotion to practice, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

283
00:26:02,443 --> 00:26:02,904
Very good.

284
00:26:03,286 --> 00:26:05,648
So I shall now do the chanting.

285
00:26:08,133 --> 00:26:09,034
That's odd.

286
00:26:09,694 --> 00:26:14,521
My computer says 25 minutes past eight, but my clock says half past eight.

287
00:26:15,211 --> 00:26:31,249
I don't know.

288
00:26:31,730 --> 00:26:42,281
Okay, we can begin.

289
00:26:48,708 --> 00:27:15,221
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

290
00:27:16,213 --> 00:27:40,163
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Bodhansaranam Gacchami Damansaranam Gacchami Sangamsaranam Gacchami

291
00:27:40,919 --> 00:28:07,482
Tuthi Ampi Bodham Saranam Gacchami Tuthi Ampi Dhammam Saranam Gacchami Tuthi Ampi Sangam Saranam Gacchami Tuthi Ampi Bodham Saranam Gacchami

292
00:28:08,154 --> 00:28:36,913
Tattyampi Damang Saranang Gacchami Tattyampi Sandang Saranang Gacchami Panatipata Velamani Sikapadan Samadhi Ami Adhinadana Velamani

293
00:28:37,180 --> 00:29:00,775
Sikapadan Samadhi Ami Kamesumi Cacera Velamani Sikapadan Samadhi Ami Musawadda Velamani Sikapadan Samadhi Ami

294
00:29:01,025 --> 00:29:26,086
So we can begin our sitting.

295
00:29:26,886 --> 00:29:30,390
So make sure you are comfortable, feeling comfortable.

296
00:29:34,758 --> 00:29:36,240
Settling on the breath.

297
00:29:39,484 --> 00:29:52,383
We can begin our sitting with these evening contemplations, which the Buddha says are there to make us more enthusiastic, to give us some real purpose as to why we're practicing.

298
00:29:55,567 --> 00:30:01,035
So just repeating these phrases to ourselves.

299
00:30:10,076 --> 00:30:37,198
This body is subject to disease This body is of a nature to fall ill This body has not gone beyond sickness This body is subject to aging

300
00:30:42,021 --> 00:31:09,800
This body has not gone beyond aging This body is now in a process of aging This body is subject to death This body has not gone beyond death

301
00:31:14,826 --> 00:31:16,209
This body will die.

302
00:31:16,249 --> 00:31:30,163
There is the unborn, undying, uncreated, uncompounded.

303
00:31:36,230 --> 00:31:37,172
The unconditioned.

304
00:31:42,451 --> 00:31:44,894
True refuge, harbour and home.

305
00:31:50,444 --> 00:31:52,848
Perfect peace and contentment.

306
00:31:59,601 --> 00:32:05,151
Those who are mindful are in the presence, in the vicinity of Nibbana.

307
00:32:27,440 --> 00:32:27,523
Thank you.

